<DOC><DOCNO> AP890405-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2212EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0818 04-05 0427</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0818,0437</SECOND><HEAD>Guerrillas Step Up Attacks After Threat</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd pvs, `Eight rebels...' to UPDATE withattack on artillery brigade. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The rebels...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas attackedarmy and civilian targets in central and eastern El Salvador onWednesday and sabotaged power lines, leaving much of the capitalwithout power.   Eight rebels were killed and seven wounded in two days ofcombat, the army said.   In the afternoon, the rebels also made an unsuccessful attack onthe Artillery Brigade in San Juan Opico, 16 miles northeast of thecapital, an army official said.   The rebels' Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front threatenedlast week to step up attacks and present President-elect AlfredoCristiani with ``an ungovernable country'' when he takes office onJune 1.   Guerrillas destroyed seven power pylons and fired rifles at armypositions in Quezaltepeque, about 16 miles northwest of SanSalvador, the armed forces press office said. No casualties werereported.   It said that in Nueva Guadalupe, 74 miles east of San Salvador,rebels early Wednesday destroyed a telecommunications office, thetown's judicial chambers and several vehicles owned by aconstruction company, and slightly damaged the local civil defenseheadquarters.   Guerrillas dynamited a textile mill in Soyapango, four mileseast of San Salvador, in an attack National Police blamed on urbancommandos of the Farabundo Marti.   Urban guerrillas exploded dynamite charges late Tuesday at 10local bank offices and destroyed five electrical pylons in thecapital, creating panic in some neighborhoods and leaving most ofthe city in darkness. One explosion slightly injured a child,officials said.   Troops exchanged gunfire with guerrillas in Jucuaran, 80 mileseast of San Salvador, killing one rebel and wounding two, the pressoffice said. It said no army casualties resulted.   The armed forces said soldiers of the Belloso counterinsurgencybattalion killed seven rebels and wounded five Tuesday in an attackon a guerrilla base camp in Suchitoto, 27 miles north of thecapital. Troops discovered mines, explosive charges and medicinesinside the camp, it said.   Troops also dismantled two guerrilla camps in northernChalantenango province, a rebel stronghold.   Ana Guadalupe Martinez, a member of the Farabundo Marti'spolitical directorate, warned last week of increased guerrillaattacks before Cristiani takes office.   Cristiani, of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, wonthe March 19 presidential elections.   The Farabundo Marti has waged a 9-year-old civil war against theU.S.-supported government. More than 70,000 Salvadorans, most ofthem civilians, have been killed.</TEXT></DOC>